{
  "id": "019d2d89-8625-7ef1-90de-d48925f4f5e2",
  "content": "# Corvia Architecture Gap Analysis vs State of the Art (March 2026)\n\n## Strengths (Where Corvia Leads)\n\n1. **Multi-Agent Coordination — Industry-Leading**: Full staging → commit → merge pipeline with RBAC, session state machines, LLM-assisted conflict resolution, git branch isolation. No competitor comes close. Mem0 uses simple user_id filtering; Zep has session-level isolation only.\n\n2. **Bi-Temporal Model — Shared Only With Zep**: Both valid_time and recorded_at tracked. Point-in-time queries (\"what did we know on March 1st?\"). O(log n) temporal index range scans.\n\n3. **Knowledge Health Reasoning — Unique**: 10 deterministic + 2 LLM-assisted health checks. No competitor has comparable validation (stale entries, broken chains, orphaned nodes, dependency cycles, coverage gaps, contradictions).\n\n4. **Zero-Docker Default — Strong for Dev Tools**: LiteStore + Redb + HNSW requires zero external services. Critical for coding agent integration where users expect npm-install simplicity.\n\n5. **Git as Truth — Unique Approach**: Knowledge JSON files in git provide diffable history, branch-based isolation, developer-familiar audit trail.\n\n## Gaps (Where Corvia Falls Behind)\n\n### Gap 1: No Explicit Knowledge Tiering (Critical)\nAll entries in same HNSW index, same Redb tables, same retrieval path. No hot/warm/cold separation. No access tracking (last_accessed, access_count). No forgetting policies (age-based, inactivity, budget). No automatic promotion/demotion. Leaders: Redis (5-stage lifecycle, 4 forgetting policies), Hindsight (confidence scores), Letta (LLM-managed paging).\n\n### Gap 2: Single-Channel Retrieval (Significant)\nVector + graph expansion is sequential, not parallel multi-channel. No BM25/keyword search (Zep has semantic + BM25 + graph at P95 300ms, zero LLM calls). No temporal weighting in retrieval despite having bi-temporal data. No multi-channel fusion with reranking. Estimated benchmark impact: 50-65% range vs Hindsight's 91.4%.\n\n### Gap 3: No Write-Time Intelligence (Significant)\nNo automatic entity extraction at ingestion. No automatic graph construction from text. No automatic fact resolution for contradicting claims. Graph edges must be explicitly created. This is the strongest emerging pattern — Zep's write-time intelligence is what separates its 63.8% from Mem0's 49.0%.\n\n### Gap 4: No Memory Consolidation / Reflection (Moderate)\nNo periodic summarization. No reflection loop for self-review. No confidence scoring on entries. Claude Code's AutoDream now consolidates every 24h. A-MEM does Zettelkasten-style autonomous linking.\n\n### Gap 5: No Standard Benchmark Results (Strategic)\nNever tested on LongMemEval or LoCoMo. Cannot credibly position against competitors without numbers. Opportunity: create a developer memory benchmark (none exists yet).\n\n## Recommended Priorities\n\n1. **Tiered knowledge with access tracking and decay** — add last_accessed/access_count, hot/warm/cold classification, forgetting policies\n2. **BM25 hybrid search** — tantivy crate, reciprocal rank fusion or cross-encoder reranking, temporal recency weighting\n3. **Write-time entity extraction and automatic graph construction** — LLM or NER at ingestion, auto-create graph edges\n4. **Memory consolidation / reflection loop** — periodic dedup, merge, summarize, flag contradictions (reuse merge worker infra)\n5. **Benchmark on LongMemEval/LoCoMo** — establish baseline, prioritize improvements\n6. **Position as embedded memory engine for coding agents** — MCP-native, zero-Docker, graph + temporal + multi-agent",
